<h2>How to get more Facebook reviews</h2>
<p>When it comes to Facebook reviews, more is more. You need at least <a href="https://www.facebook.com/help/500762053364226" target="_blank" rel="noopener">five reviews</a> to get a rating for your page, but this is a minimum. You want to amass enough reviews that they reflect all of your different customer types and reference all of your core products and offerings.</p>
<p>The most effective way to get more reviews is to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/07/16/how-to-ask-for-reviews">ask for them</a>. Hereâ€™s how to do that.</p>
<h3>Send follow-up emails after a purchase or service</h3>
<p>You probably already have automations set up for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/07/07/thank-you-for-your-order-messages">thank you emails</a> post-purchase and shipping updates, if those are relevant. One effective, straightforward strategy to get more Facebook reviews is to add an automated check-in email.</p>
<p>This should arrive a week or two after a completed order to see how your customers are enjoying their purchase. Did everything arrive in good condition? Were the services satisfactory? Do they have any immediate feedback? And, most importantly, if theyâ€™re happy with the purchase and results, would they be interested in leaving a review?</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/review-request-email-example-png.webp" alt="review request email example" width="528" height="900" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91180" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/review-request-email-example-png.webp 528w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/review-request-email-example-480x818.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 528px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Two things to be aware of with these emails. First, make it easy to submit a review. Include a button (like the email example above) linking directly to your Facebook review page.</p>
<p>And second, be sure to actually respond to any feedbackâ€”positive and especially negative. You donâ€™t want to ignore an unhappy customer who is willing to reach out.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4eb.png" alt="ðŸ“«" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Get everything you need for great emails (even review request emails!) &gt;&gt;</strong> <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/email-examples-and-templates?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_Email_EmailTemplates_Download&amp;itm_source=wordstream&amp;itm_medium=blog&amp;itm_campaign=incontent_links">The Complete Email Marketing Toolkit: Free Email Templates, Subject Lines &amp; Tips</a></p>
<h3>Request reviews in your receipts or invoices</h3>
<p>For plenty of giant corporations, including a <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/qr-code-marketing/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">QR code</a> leading to a review site on a physical receipt or a link to submit review in an emailed receipt is common practice. This is something that your businessâ€”small or medium, ecommerce or in-person servicesâ€”can do, too.</p>
<h3>Ask customers directly</h3>
<p>If you do business in person, make sure to ask your customers directly for a review. If you have a services business, add this to your final goodbye when a happy client thanks you for a job well done. If you have a brick-and-mortar store, include the prompt to leave a Facebook review in your regular checkout script. Or save the request for your enthusiasts and return customers.</p>
<p>And itâ€™s good to keep in mind that customers wonâ€™t be thrown by this request. BrightLocal found that <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/research/local-consumer-review-survey-2024/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">28%</a> of customers reported they&#8217;d prefer to be asked to leave reviews in person (second only to email requests).</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/how-customers-want-to-be-asked-to-leave-reviews-png.webp" alt="how customers want to be asked to leave reviews from brightlocal survey" width="831" height="900" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91189" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/how-customers-want-to-be-asked-to-leave-reviews-png.webp 831w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/how-customers-want-to-be-asked-to-leave-reviews-480x520.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 831px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>Post on your Facebook page with a clear CTA</h3>
<p>Another option is to ask your customers to leave a review when theyâ€™re already on Facebook. Post an update requesting reviews for your page, and include the direct link to get started submitting one.</p>
<p>Americans over 18 spend an average of <a href="https://explodingtopics.com/blog/social-media-usage#spending-time-on-facebook" target="_blank" rel="noopener">31 minutes</a> on Facebook each day. While theyâ€™re scrolling past updates and ads, or if theyâ€™re checking your business page for hours or sales, theyâ€™ll see your postâ€”and best case scenario, theyâ€™ll leave a review.</p>
<p>Just remember, you donâ€™t want to do this too often. Asking for reviews is great. Looking like youâ€™re begging or bugging your followers? Not a good tactic.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4da.png" alt="ðŸ“š" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" />Â <strong>Free guide download</strong>Â &gt;&gt;Â <a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSLIQContentDLWebsite36CallToActionPhrases.html?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_36CallToActionPhrases_Download">The 42 Best Call to Action Phrases Ever (&amp; Why They Work)</a></p>
<h3>Include a link in your email template</h3>
<p>The <a href="https://www.ftc.gov/business-guidance/resources/can-spam-act-compliance-guide-business" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CAN-SPAM Act </a>requires that you include a few things in your email, like your physical location and a clear and correct option for unsubscribing. Most <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/small-business-email-examples-and-templates/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">marketing email templates</a> put these in a footer so that they appear in every single email sent to ensure compliance. But you donâ€™t have to stop there.</p>
<p>You can also include a subtle request for reviews in your email footer. Depending on your template or your companyâ€™s <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/07/01/email-marketing-tips">email marketing strategy</a>, you could also include this request to leave a review on Facebook in your employee email signatures.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/review-request-in-email-signature-png.webp" alt="example of review request in email signature" width="607" height="403" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91181" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/review-request-in-email-signature-png.webp 607w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/review-request-in-email-signature-480x319.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 607px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>Text your subscribed customers about review promotions</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/sms-marketing-examples">SMS marketing</a> is another good channel to reach your customers with a simple, direct request for a review, especially after a recent transaction. Simple Texting found that <a href="https://simpletexting.com/blog/2024-texting-and-sms-marketing-statistics/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">79%</a> of consumers opted into receiving text messages from businesses in 2024. Iâ€™m definitely one of them. Iâ€™ve submitted my phone number in exchange for a 15% off discountâ€¦ and proceeded to stay subscribed and click on the sales offers too many times.</p>
<p>But as long as youâ€™re using SMS marketing sparingly and purposefully, adding a prompt to leave a Facebook review after purchase is a great way to get more reviews.</p>
<h3>Leverage a chatbot script</h3>
<p>If youâ€™re using a chatbot on your website, you can create a script with a prompt to leave a Facebook review to target relevant conversations with customers. In fact, some businesses have seen great success using this tactic.</p>
<p>Andrey Lipkovskiy shared the breakdown of a chatbot experiment they ran to generate more Facebook reviews <a href="https://manychat.com/blog/generate-customer-reviews-with-chatbots/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Manychat blog</a>. The results were overwhelming. An 87% open rate, a 24% CTA, and 65 new 5-star reviews in just 24 hours. Worth a try.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/manychat-reviews-status-on-facebook-png.webp" alt="reviews standing for manychat on facebook" width="600" height="433" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91177" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/manychat-reviews-status-on-facebook-png.webp 600w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/manychat-reviews-status-on-facebook-480x346.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 600px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Image via Manychat</em></p>
<h3>Use positive reviews in your marketing materials</h3>
<p>Another subtle way to call attention to your Facebook reviews is to use those customer testimonials in your marketing materials. You can feature these in display ads, Instagram or Facebook ads, Google Adsâ€”there are tons of options. And the good news is that these are effective for sales, as well. One case study found that using testimonials on sales pages, for instance, increased purchases by <a href="https://vwo.com/success-stories/wikijob/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">34%</a>.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/reviews-in-facebook-ad-png.webp" alt="star rating showing in facebook ad" width="509" height="495" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91179" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/reviews-in-facebook-ad-png.webp 509w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/reviews-in-facebook-ad-480x467.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 509px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>Avoid offering a discount or running a giveaway</h3>
<p>Technically, the <a href="https://www.ftc.gov/business-guidance/resources/soliciting-paying-online-reviews-guide-marketers" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Federal Trade Commission</a> allows you to incentivize reviews as long as you incentivize positive and negative reviews equally and the compensation is disclosed in the body of the review. But many platforms, including Etsy and Google, prohibit this because it makes reviews less trustworthy.</p>
<p>Facebook doesnâ€™t explicitly prohibit compensation for reviews, but itâ€™s still better to avoid. Especially because it undermines the authority in all of your other reviews, even ones you earned from happy, uncompensated customers.</p>
<div id="how-to-manage-facebook-reviews"></div>
<h2>How to manage your Facebook reviews</h2>
<p>Getting more Facebook reviews is important, but so is following through on managing those reviews. You need to be paying attention to your page, responding in a timely manner, and keeping track of your overall business score to ensure that these Facebook reviews remain a tool to help grow your business.</p>
<p>Hereâ€™s how.</p>
<h3>Make sure your reviews are enabled and visible</h3>
<p>This is the first step because itâ€™s the most basic. <strong>In order to get Facebook reviews on your business page, you need to enable reviews in your profile. </strong>Luckily, itâ€™s easy to do.</p>
<ol>
<li>First, go to your page.</li>
<li>Next, click on settings.</li>
<li>When the new window appears, click on the â€œTemplates and Tabsâ€ section.</li>
<li>Toggle reviews â€œOn.â€</li>
</ol>
<p>And thatâ€™s it. Simple, but essential. You can also change the order so that the tab containing reviews appears early.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/facebook-business-page-reviews-tab-example-png.webp" alt="facebook business page reviews tab" width="1200" height="683" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91184" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/facebook-business-page-reviews-tab-example-png.webp 1200w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/facebook-business-page-reviews-tab-example-980x558.webp 980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/facebook-business-page-reviews-tab-example-480x273.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) 1200px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>Have your Facebook review link handy</h3>
<p>When youâ€™re asking people to leave a review, you need to direct them to the correct place. So make sure you have a link directly to your review page stored in a readily accessible location. Whether itâ€™s in your email signature, in a shared note or document with all your review and social links, or in your companyâ€™s project and document database is up to you and depends on what works best for your team and your business. The important thing is that itâ€™s easy to access.</p>
<p>And make sure other members of your team have easy access, too, and know where to find the link. You never know when someone might want to ask for a Facebook review.</p>
<h3>Set up automated notifications for new reviews</h3>
<p>To manage your Facebook reviews, you need to know when you have a new one. Checking regularly is good practice, but to save yourself time, you can set up automatic notifications for any new review.</p>
<p>On your Facebook business page, go to the â€œNotificationsâ€ tab and make sure youâ€™ve got the â€œNew Reviewsâ€ options selected.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/5-star-facebook-review-moving-service-png.webp" alt="5-star review for a moving service on facebook" width="451" height="272" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91178" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/5-star-facebook-review-moving-service-png.webp 451w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/5-star-facebook-review-moving-service-300x181.webp 300w" sizes="(max-width: 451px) 100vw, 451px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>You want to be able to respond to a glowing review like this ASAP.</em></p>
<h3>Respond to all reviews</h3>
<p>You need to <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/how-to-respond-to-google-reviews-with-examples/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">respond to all of your reviews</a>. This is not only a good practice, itâ€™s also important for ensuring a good Facebook business rating (more on this later) and boosting your brandâ€™s trustworthiness. Studies show that businesses that respond to customer reviews are perceived as <a href="https://grow.google/intl/en_my/article-how-to-respond-to-reviews-on-google/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">1.7 times</a> more trustworthy than brands who donâ€™t respond.</p>
<p>Remember that your responses should be individualized when itâ€™s called for, too. This is true for an exceptional and personal review as well as your negative reviews. When a frustrated customer reaches out, you should validate and accept their feedback, apologize for the poor experience, and provide a venue for follow-up communication to resolve the issue. And this brings us to our next step.</p>
<h3>Follow up with action on negative reviews</h3>
<p>When you have <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/how-to-respond-to-negative-reviews/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">negative reviews</a> that are specifically about a poor experience or a disappointing purchase, you need to follow up with an action. This should first be a follow-up communication off of your Facebook page, either a direct email or a phone call. And if possible, you should offer a solution to rectify the situation, like a replacement item, a discount, or a correction in your services.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/negative-facebook-review-example-plus-response-png.webp" alt="example of a negative facebook review with a response" width="1066" height="601" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91188" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/negative-facebook-review-example-plus-response-png.webp 1066w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/negative-facebook-review-example-plus-response-980x553.webp 980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/negative-facebook-review-example-plus-response-480x271.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) 1066px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>A good prompt response that validates and promises a follow-up action.</em></p>
<h3>Flag inappropriate or fake content right away</h3>
<p>Now, letâ€™s be clear. You canâ€™t curate your Facebook reviews (and you canâ€™t delete them just because you donâ€™t like them). Negative reviews will stay there (and thatâ€™s not always bad), and lukewarm recommendations will be visible, too. But if there is content that is inappropriate, itâ€™s your responsibility to report it. If itâ€™s a fake review, you want to report it.</p>
<p>You can do so easily by clicking the three dots (&#8230;) next to the review, selecting â€œâ€‹â€‹Find Support or Report Review,â€ and then following the prompts.</p>
<p>Unfortunately, this wonâ€™t delete the content automatically, but it is the first step in removing it from your page.</p>
<h3>Monitor your Facebook business score</h3>
<p>Before 2018, all Facebook reviews included star ratings. In 2018, the platform changed the format of reviews to a simple question: â€œDo you recommend the business or not?â€ Then, respondents have the opportunity to include a narrative review.</p>
<p>Once your page has five or more Facebook reviews, the platform will assign your business a rating. According to <a href="https://www.facebook.com/business/help/579645403238373" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Meta</a>, this rating reflects an average of your customersâ€™ satisfaction with your business and your products or services. This includes your recommendations as well as your reviews.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/facebook-business-page-recommended-percentage-png.webp" alt="facebook business page recommended percentage" width="1200" height="753" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91185" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/facebook-business-page-recommended-percentage-png.webp 1200w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/facebook-business-page-recommended-percentage-980x615.webp 980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/facebook-business-page-recommended-percentage-480x301.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) 1200px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Here, the rating appears with other relevant information right on the Facebook business page.</em></p>
<p>Unfortunately, you donâ€™t have much control over this rating or visibility into the specific weighting system. Thatâ€™s why itâ€™s especially important to keep an eye on it.</p>
<h3>Optimize your Facebook business page</h3>
<p>Youâ€™re putting a lot of effort into generating Facebook reviews and monitoring this feedback from your customers. Make sure youâ€™re paying attention to the rest of your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2017/10/16/facebook-business-page">Facebook business page</a>, too.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/facebook-business-page-example-landmark-fine-homes-png.webp" alt="facebook business page for landmark fine homes" width="870" height="900" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91190" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/facebook-business-page-example-landmark-fine-homes-png.webp 870w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/facebook-business-page-example-landmark-fine-homes-480x497.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 870px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>On brand and up to date.</em></p>
<p>If your customers are on the platform, take advantage of this. Post regular updates, share shoppable links, and ensure all of your business informationâ€”especially hours and contact informationâ€”is up to date.</p>
<h2>Use this guide to get more Facebook reviews</h2>
<p>Okay, this was a lot on Facebook reviews to cover. But keep in mind that most of the setup steps are one-offsâ€”important, but quick to go through. The key is to set up automated solicitations for reviews, make a habit of asking for Facebook reviews when itâ€™s possible, and keep track of new reviews when they come in.</p>
<p>Now, youâ€™re equipped with everything you need to know to get started growing your Facebook reviews. Good luck!</p>
