										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>LinkedIn is a massive platform that keeps on growing year after year. As the user base expands, there are more opportunities for industry niches, rising star influencers, and must-follow business accounts.</p>
<p>But that also means more engaging content competes for attention from users and LinkedInâ€™s algorithm. Of course, youâ€™ll need to be on top of things like content quality and publishing frequency. But thereâ€™s another logistical concern to consider: Whatâ€™s the best time to post on LinkedIn to be maximally competitive?</p>
<p>Here, weâ€™re covering everything you need to know about when to post on LinkedIn. Plus, weâ€™ll walk you through how to check your analytics. That way, you can keep refining your schedule once you know the best and worst times to engage your own audience on LinkedIn.</p>
<h3>Contents</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#why-does-it-matter-when-you-post-on-linkedin">Why does it matter when you post on LinkedIn?</a></li>
<li><a href="#best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-overall">Whatâ€™s the best time to post on LinkedIn overall?</a></li>
<li><a href="#best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-for-your-industry">Whatâ€™s the best time to post on LinkedIn for your industry?</a></li>
<li><a href="#best-days-to-post-on-linkedin">What are the best days to post on LinkedIn?</a></li>
<li><a href="#worst-days-to-post-on-linkedin">What are the worst days to post on LinkedIn?</a></li>
<li><a href="#find-best-and-worst-times-to-post-on-linkedin">How do you find the best and worst times to post on LinkedIn for your audience?</a></li>
</ul>
<div id="why-does-it-matter-when-you-post-on-linkedin"></div>
<h2>Why does it matter when you post on LinkedIn?</h2>
<p>The time you <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/generating-leads-on-linkedin">post on LinkedIn</a> impacts how your post is sorted, coded, and amplified by the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/11/08/linkedin-pulse">platformâ€™s algorithm</a>. So, posting at the right times means a better chance your content gets in front of more people.</p>
<p>When you sign into your <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/linkedin-company-page/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LinkedIn page</a>, your feed is automatically sorted by â€œtopâ€ posts, as opposed to a chronological order of the most recent.</p>
<p>LinkedIn users <em>can</em> switch manually to the most recent if they choose to do that. But theyâ€™d have to do it every single time they log in. Thatâ€™s because the platform wants to serve the posts identified as â€œtopâ€ by the algorithm first. Since most people wonâ€™t go through that trouble, â€œtopâ€ posts are seen the most.</p>
<p>Hereâ€™s my view, as an example.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-LinkedIn-post-png.webp" alt="Best time to post on LinkedIn - screenshot from LinkedIn account." width="774" height="880" class="aligncenter wp-image-90013 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-LinkedIn-post-png.webp 774w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-LinkedIn-post-480x546.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 774px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>The top post is liked by Allen Finn, a marketer who previously wrote for the WordStream blog and regularly posts on LinkedIn (also relevant here is the fact that Iâ€™m married to him).</p>
<p>The actual content is shared by Emily Kramer, who runs the educational newsletter and advising program for marketers <a href="https://www.mkt1.co/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MKT1</a>. She also has nearly 35,000 followers on LinkedIn, where she regularly shares this type of deep-diving, insightful content.</p>
<p>My experience with LinkedIn here tells us a lot about how the algorithm works. For example, the LinkedIn algorithm prioritizes:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Accounts that you regularly interact with or are closely connected with: </strong>This includes accounts you engage with and follow.</li>
<li><strong>Accounts that other profiles comparable to yours interact with: </strong><a href="https://localiq.com/blog/linkedin-profile-tips/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Profiles</a> comparable to yours may have the same industry experience, similar companies, close job titles, or even matching keywords in your bios.</li>
<li><strong>Posts with high engagement, especially in the form of substantive comments: </strong>The key word here is substantive. Those posts asking for a single emoji â€œvoteâ€? LinkedIn is ruling these out.</li>
<li><strong>Posts with high-quality content: </strong>This means no spam or spam-like text or images, no clickbait with a million lines of only one or two words to entice a â€œsee moreâ€ click.</li>
</ul>
<p>If youâ€™re wondering what spam is, hereâ€™s how LinkedIn detects it.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-spam-chart-png.webp" alt="Best time to post on LinkedIn - LinkedIn's process chart for detecting spam." width="1024" height="595" class="aligncenter wp-image-90015 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-spam-chart-png.webp 1024w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-spam-chart-980x569.webp 980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-spam-chart-480x279.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) 1024px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>According to </em><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/blog/engineering/trust-and-safety/viral-spam-content-detection-at-linkedin" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>LinkedIn</em></a><em>, this is the model for spam detection.</em></p>
<p>So what does this have to do with the timing of your LinkedIn posts, you might be wondering?</p>
<p>The answer is all about engagement. The faster you can get engagement on a post, the more likely the algorithm will prioritize your post for more users. Then, the flywheel kicks in because more people will engage with your post, and the algorithm will show it to even more people.</p>
<p>So, timing your post for the most early engagement is key to getting more overall engagement. Hereâ€™s how to do it.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4e3.png" alt="ðŸ“£" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /><strong> Want a yearâ€™s worth of social media content? </strong>Download <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/social-media-calendar-template?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Template_MonthlySocialMediaCalendar_Download">Your Copy &amp; Paste Social Media Calendar</a> and get it right now!</p>
