<h2>How do you find the best and worst times to post on LinkedIn for your audience?</h2>
<p>The guidance above is valuable for setting your schedule and cadence for posting on LinkedIn. But to keep <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/social-media-strategy">growing your account</a>, you need to get more specific with the better, more accurate data you have access to.</p>
<p>That means reviewing your postsâ€™ performance and your audienceâ€™s behaviors to determine the best and worst times to post on LinkedIn. Hereâ€™s how.</p>
<ol>
<li>First, on your company page, click on the analytics tab from the left-hand menu.<img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-analytics-menu-png.webp" alt="Best time to post on LinkedIn - LinkedIn Analytics menu." width="302" height="942" class="aligncenter wp-image-90017 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-analytics-menu-png.webp 302w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-analytics-menu-96x300.webp 96w" sizes="(max-width: 302px) 100vw, 302px" /></li>
<li>Then, select â€œContentâ€ from the Analytics menu. You should also set a date range, whether itâ€™s by month, quarter, or a look at the last year.<img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-analytics-time-range-1024x218.webp" alt="Best time to post on LinkedIn - analytics date range." width="1024" height="218" class="aligncenter wp-image-90019 size-large" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-analytics-time-range-1024x218.webp 1024w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-analytics-time-range-300x64.webp 300w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-analytics-time-range-768x163.webp 768w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-analytics-time-range-1080x230.webp 1080w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-analytics-time-range-980x208.webp 980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-analytics-time-range-480x102.webp 480w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/best-time-to-post-on-linkedin-wordstream-analytics-time-range-png.webp 1194w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></li>
<li>On the Content page, you will see a drop-down option to look at impressions, members reached, clicks, comments, reactions, reposts, and engagement rates. Once you select a metric to focus on, youâ€™ll see a visualization. If you scroll down, youâ€™ll also be able to look at the performance metrics for each individual post.</li>
<li>Take a look at patterns with days of the week. Unfortunately, LinkedIn wonâ€™t add in the time for each post. But you can export the data and add this yourself to identify patterns (specifically, the times that posts tend to perform well and the times when they donâ€™t).</li>
<li>Use this data to inform your posting schedule, and keep checking on it to refine your plan and grow your account.</li>
</ol>
<h2>TL;DR: When to post on LinkedIn</h2>
<p>Overall, the best times to post on LinkedIn are Tuesdays and Thursdays between 10 a.m. and 12 p.m. in your local time zone. The worst times are over the weekends when the professional platform is a bit of a dead zone.</p>
